 Loire, France":"Berry, Cher, Centre, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sully","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armelle, Christophe, Geralde, Luce, Pierre, Reynald.","English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from any of the three places called Sully in Calvados (Normandy), Aisne (Picardy), and Loiret (Centre); see 6 below.","English: of Norman origin, perhaps a habitational name from Sully (Glamorgan). However, the placename is manorial in origin, from the Norman surname in 1 above, which is recorded in Glamorgan in the 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Soley","meanings":["English: variant of   Sully  .","Catalan: variant of <b>Solell</b>, a topographic name from <i>solell</i> ‘sunny side, southern slope’, from a derivative of <i>sol</i> ‘sun’. Compare   Sol   2."]},{"name":"Solley","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Sully  ."]},{"name":"Solly","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Sully  .","Irish: variant of   Salley  ."]}]},{"name":"Iseul","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isolde  , also occasionally used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"lif